    <body>
      <section>
       {{>navbar}}
    </section>
      <div class="tech-details">
        <p class="number"><span>03</span>
          SPACE LUNCH 101
       </p>
       <div class="spaces">
         <div class="num-space">
          <form id="btn-select" action="" style="color: white;">
            <input
             type="radio" value="01" class="hidebx" id="detail1" onclick="ShowBtn('detail',3)" name="PlanetNames">
            <label for="detail1" class="select-btn active" 
            >1</label>

            <input type="radio" value="02" class="hidebx" id="detail2" onclick="ShowBtn('detail',3)" name="PlanetNames">
            <label class="select-btn" for="detail2">2</label>

            <input type="radio" value="europa" class="hidebx" id="detail3" onclick="ShowBtn('detail',3)" name="PlanetNames">
            <label class="select-btn" for="detail3">3</label>
        </form>
         </div>
         <div class="space-nav">
         <div class="space-details" id="detail1Div" style="display: flex;">
           <div class="space-texts">
             <p>THE TERMINOLOGY
             </p>
             <span class="l-text">LUNCH VEHICLE</span>
             <p>
              A launch vehicle or carrier rocket is a rocket-propelled vehicle  used to carry a payload from Earth's surface to space, usually to Earth orbit or beyond. Our WEB-x carrier rocket is the most powerful in operation. Standing 150 meters tall, it's quite an awe-inspiring sight on the launch pad!
             </p>
           </div>
         
         <div class="space-img">
            <img class="d-img" src="/assets/technology/image-launch-vehicle-portrait.jpg" alt="">
            <img class="m-img" src="/assets/technology/image-launch-vehicle-landscape.jpg" alt="">
         </div>
         </div>
         <div class="space-details" id="detail2Div" style="display: none;">
          <div class="space-texts">
            <p>THE TERMINOLOGY
            </p>
            <span class="l-text">SPACE CAPSULE</span>
            <p>
             A space capsule is an often-crewed spacecraft that uses a blunt-body reentry capsule to reenter the Earth's atmosphere without wings. Capsules are distinguished from satellites primarily by the ability to survive reentry and return a payload to the Earth's surface from orbit.
            </p>
          </div>
        
        <div class="space-img">
           <img class="d-img" src="/assets/technology/image-space-capsule-portrait.jpg" alt="">
           <img class="m-img" src="/assets/technology/image-space-capsule-landscape.jpg" alt="">
        </div>
        </div> 
        <div class="space-details" id="detail3Div" style="display: none;">
          <div class="space-texts">
            <p>THE TERMINOLOGY
            </p>
            <span class="l-text">SPACEPORT</span>
            <p>
             A spaceport or cosmodrome is a site for launching (or receiving) spacecraft, by analogy to a seaport for ships or an airport for aircraft. ... The term rocket launch site is used for any facility from which rockets are launched.
            </p>
          </div>
        
        <div class="space-img">
           <img class="d-img" src="/assets/technology/image-spaceport-portrait.jpg" alt="">
           <img class="m-img" src="/assets/technology/image-spaceport-landscape.jpg" alt="">
        </div>
        </div>  
        </div>
       </div>

      </div>

    <script>
      function ShowBtn(idName,NumOfBtn){
                for(x=1; x<=NumOfBtn; x++){
                    CheckThisBtn = idName + x;
                    ThisDiv=idName + x +'Div';
                    if(document.getElementById(CheckThisBtn).checked){
                        document.getElementById(ThisDiv).style.display="flex";
                    }
                    else{
                        document.getElementById(ThisDiv).style.display="none";
                    }
                }
                return false;
            }
    </script>
